.TH DIFF(1),User Commands,DIFF(1)

.SH NAME
diff - compare two text files line by line

.SH SYNOPSIS
diff [-uqih] [-U N] [--] file1 file2

.SH DESCRIPTION
diff compares file1 and file2 line by line and reports the differences.
Either filename may be - or #stdin to read from standard input.

diff uses the Myers O(ND) algorithm and loads both files into extended memory banks.
The maximum supported input is 300 lines per file, with each line up to 127 characters long.
The edit distance is capped at 35; files that differ by more than 35 line-level insertions or deletions cannot be diffed.

By default, diff prints a minimal summary of changes.
The -u option produces unified-diff output with context, suitable for patch(1) tools.

.SH OPTIONS
-u: Unified output format.
Print a standard unified-diff with context lines around each hunk.

-U N: Like -u, but use N lines of context around each hunk.
Default context is 3 lines.

-q: Quiet.
Report only whether the files differ, suppressing the actual diff output.

-i: Ignore case when comparing lines.

-h: Print a short usage summary and exit 2.

--: End of options. Subsequent arguments are treated as filenames.

.SH EXIT STATUS
0: Files are identical.

1: Files differ.

2: Usage error, file could not be read, or diff exceeded internal limits.

.SH EXAMPLES
Unified diff:

$ diff -u old.c new.c

Quiet check:

$ diff -q a.txt b.txt

Case-insensitive:

$ diff -i README readme
